Jul 15 2006	One star: Wouldn't recommend to a friend	We stayed there five days in June 2006 in a double. First, it was hot in London. And, our room was on the top floor (no elevator by the way.) 1) Loud and hot: The window was a single pane glass. So at night, it was so loud that we couldn't sleep until 3AM when people outside started going to bed, and traffic died down. And, it was so hot with no A/C that we couldn't even get comfortable. After walking around London and sightseeing for 12 hours per day, you want to be able to go back to an air conditioned room. So, we sweated all day, and went home and sweated at night. It was miserable. 2) Terrible bed: The bed was like a foam stuffed bag with springs sticking into us. It was probably the cheapest bed that they could find. 3) Dirty towels and linens: The towels were about as thin and cheap as a one star in the United States. To make matters worse, they didn't wash them for three days. So you had to hang up your dirty towels to dry every day. The U.K. law for Hotels is to wash at least every three days in London. So, Blades does the bare minimum required by law. 4) Tiny bathroom. This bathroom was obviously an add on. So what you have is a small bedroom room about 12 feet by 9 feet. And inside that room is a tiny shower/toilet: about 5 feet by 2.5 feet. 5) Non-English staff. If you want an English B&amp;B experience you can't get it at Blades. The staff is not from England. Nothing wrong with the people, however, if you are in London, you want to have someone who has lived there their whole life to give you tips and interesting conversation. The owner/manager Kevin made a cameo appearance one day. He is great, but not around. 6) location: It is not by Victoria Station, it is one stop after Victoria station. Since you will use the Tube everyday to go to Westminister or the Tower, you should stay near Westminister. That way you can save the $9/day on Tube tickets for two people. Add that to the cost of the Hotel room and it is about $155/ night. So for the same price or perhaps $20 more, you can stay in an air conditioned 3-4 star hotel with washed towels, elevator, comfortable bed, and a good nights sleep. It is ridiculous to stay at Blades for that price when you can get comfort for the same price on the other side of the Thames in Westminister. 7) Breakfast was lame: I don't know why they advertise a &quot;hearty breakfast&quot; - it is essentially Wheaties, yougurt, bread, and some canned mixed fruit. The meat is ham cold cuts. Yum. 8) customer service: when we complained it was too hot, and loud to sleep the young lady working there immediately blamed us. She said, &quot;why don't you wear earplugs? Aren't you tired from walking all day? You should have no problem sleeping - you must not be walking enough.&quot; Meanwhile, we walked 12 hours per day, and the room was sweltering. She did move us though to the back of the house which was much quieter.	
